🧠 Math Power Tier List (by expressive + structural power)

🟢 Tier C — “Local Tools” (useful but bounded)

These operate on specific objects, not systems.
	•	Arithmetic
	•	Basic Algebra
	•	Geometry
	•	Trigonometry

Power:
	•	Solve direct problems
	•	Concrete, intuitive

Limitation:
	•	No deep abstraction
	•	Doesn’t generalize far

⸻

🔵 Tier B — “System Builders”

Now we model change, space, and uncertainty.
	•	Calculus
	•	Linear Algebra
	•	Differential Equations
	•	Probability / Statistics

Power:
	•	Models real-world systems
	•	Bridges math ↔ physics ↔ engineering

Key upgrade:

You move from solving → modeling

⸻

🟣 Tier A — “Structure & Symmetry”

This is where math becomes about math itself.
	•	Abstract Algebra (groups, rings, fields)
	•	Topology
	•	Differential Geometry
	•	Complex Analysis

Power:
	•	Studies invariants (what doesn’t change)
	•	Works across domains

Key upgrade:

You stop studying objects → you study relationships between objects

⸻

🔴 Tier S — “Translation Layers”

These are insanely powerful because they convert problems into solvable forms.
	•	Representation Theory
	•	Fourier / Harmonic Analysis
	•	Functional Analysis

Power:
	•	Turn hard problems → easy ones via transformation
	•	Reveal hidden structure

Key upgrade:

“Find the right coordinate system and the problem collapses”

⸻

🟡 Tier SS — “Meta-Structure / Logic Layer”

Now we’re above math—designing math itself.
	•	Category Theory
	•	Mathematical Logic
	•	Type Theory
	•	Set Theory (foundations)

Power:
	•	Describes all mathematical structures
	•	Unifies fields

Key upgrade:

Math becomes a language about transformations and mappings

⸻

⚫ Tier SSS — “Reality Interface / Frontier”

This is where math touches the edge of reality and unknown structure.
	•	Algebraic Geometry
	•	Number Theory (deep end)
	•	Langlands Program
	•	Information Theory
	•	Quantum Mathematics

Power:
	•	Links distant domains
	•	Encodes deep structure of reality

Key upgrade:

Math becomes a compression of reality itself

